data.content:
Your code doesn't actually use `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort` anywhere. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed** for this code.

That said, as a modernization improvement, consider replacing raw `Thread` usage with `Task.WhenAll` and `Parallel.ForEachAsync`, which are idiomatic in modern .NET and naturally support `CancellationToken` if you need cancellation later:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

